Headlines.Author: Mia Lamar
Headlines.Headline: JM Smucker 1Q Profit Up 8.4%, Margin Slides On High Raw Material Costs

PARAGRAPH.#text: J.M. Smucker Co.'s SJM fiscal first-quarter earnings improved 8.4% yet profit margins came under pressure due to continued high costs for raw materials. The food company, which gets most of its revenue from U.S. retail coffee, earlier this week said it cut coffee prices on most of its coffee products sold in the U.S. by an average of 6%. That decision came after a year in which the company raised prices a total of 23% in an effort to battle soaring costs. Thursday, Smucker said it expects that the company will continue to recognize steep green coffee costs in the year ahead, particularly in its second quarter.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By William L. Watts U.S. stock futures slumped on Thursday, as fears over global growth prospects and Europe's ongoing sovereign debt problems weighed on equity markets around the world. Standard & Poor's 500 index futures dropped 21.2 points to 1168.70, while Nasdaq 100 futures lost 44.25 points to trade at 2131. #text: Semiconductor distributor Avnet

warned that it would not meet the consensus Street estimate of 85 cents for the current quarter. The company warned that "a better estimate" would be between 75 cents and 80 cents, double last year's comparable quarter. In a statement, company CEO, Roy Vallee said, "Because we believe this correction is temporary, our expectations for the second half of fiscal 2001 EPS performance have not changed; however, this will lower the annual EPS consensus estimate of $3.46 by $0.05 or $0.10."
